solution.approach:
Create a config file at `eval/drift/config.yaml` in the workload repository, declaring:

- the per-dimension metrics to monitor (rubric-dimension scores for catalogue authoring; accuracy / precision / recall for an ML model; retrieval-hit-rate or answer-grounding for RAG; whatever the workload exposes);
- per-dimension baseline values anchored to the workload's deployment (the model version and harness version the baseline is from);
- per-dimension cadence (daily, weekly, per-event);
- per-dimension alert thresholds (window-to-window drop; optionally a cumulative-from-baseline drop);
- alert routing (channel and recipients).

Build or adopt a scheduled monitor runtime that runs the declared metrics on cadence and logs per-dimension scores to a known location (`eval/drift/runs/`). Build or adopt an alerter runtime that watches those logs and dispatches alerts per the declared routing when thresholds are crossed.

When the deployed model is updated (model version, prompt version, agent configuration that materially affects outputs), update the baseline reference in `eval/drift/config.yaml` OR commit an ADR under `docs/adrs/` justifying why the existing baseline still holds.

The config file (the metrics list, baselines, cadences, thresholds, routing) is what Gate 1 inspects; the monitor and alerter runtimes are workload-level engineering choices this principle does not gate directly.

Maintain a versioned model-selection decision record at a known repository path (convention `model-selection/decision.md` or equivalent ADR location under the workload repository). The record names:

- the minimum performance requirements the model must meet (the criteria considered, absorbing the substance of AWS step 1);
- the candidate models evaluated against those requirements (the shortlist, absorbing AWS step 2);
- the chosen model;
- the cost-aware rationale tying the choice to the prioritized cost dimensions (hosting paradigm, model size, token cost).

Wire two pre-merge CI gates against the record: an existence + content-completeness gate, and a coupling gate that requires any PR adding or changing a model reference to update the decision record.

The baseline mandate (Option A — declared-and-verified, config-derivable) requires every vector store to commit a small declaration alongside its index configuration: a record (convention `vectorstore/embedding.yaml`, or an equivalent manifest row) carrying:

- `embedding_model`;
- `vector_dimension` (the dimension the index is embedded at);
- `quality_floor` (the named retrieval metric and threshold that the dimension must clear, e.g. top-5 recall >= 0.95);
- `quality_result` (the measured value at the chosen dimension that justifies it);
- `checked_on`.

A central lint (convention `vectorstore/dimension_check`) enforces three things at pre-merge:

- **Declaration completeness** — the declaration exists and every field is populated; the build fails when it is absent or any field is blank, forcing the dimension to be a recorded decision rather than a silent default.
- **Deployed-vs-declared consistency** — it parses the vector-store index configuration (the Terraform / IaC resource, or the index-creation call: Pinecone / pgvector / OpenSearch / Weaviate index definitions) and fails when the dimension of the actually-provisioned index differs from the declared `vector_dimension`, closing the declared-number-is-fiction case.
- **Dimension-inflation governance** — any PR raising `vector_dimension` above its previous committed value (diffed against the merge base) must carry a recorded cost/quality rationale (a `change_history` entry in the declaration or a linked ADR under `docs/adrs/`); the lint fails an upward change without one, closing the quietly-raised-for-quality case.

All three checks are config-derivable — no fixtures, no deployed runtime — so they fire at review time, before the corpus is embedded and the dimension is locked in. The gate deliberately enforces that a quality number is recorded and that the deployed dimension is real and stable; it does NOT itself re-run the retrieval evaluation, because measuring retrieval quality at a candidate dimension leans on a retrieval-eval harness (the GO1B1 family's analogue for retrieval, and GENPERF04 territory) rather than a config lint.

One alternative reference implementation is documented for workloads wanting the gate to enforce 'smallest that works' directly and MAY be adopted in addition to (not instead of) the Option A baseline: **Option B (measured-from-retrieval-eval)** runs the candidate corpus through a retrieval-quality harness at several dimensions and gates the chosen `vector_dimension` against the smallest size that clears the declared `quality_floor`, failing the build when a smaller eligible dimension would have met the bar — closer to enforcing the mandate, at the cost of coupling to a representative retrieval-eval fixture set and a re-embed of the eval corpus.

The reference implementation at `data/ri/GC4B1-01/README.md` is built on Option A.
